{
  "card_id": "candlestick_pattern",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Candlestick Pattern",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A candlestick pattern is a formation of one or more candlesticks that visualizes market sentiment through real body size and wick length, indicating potential reversals or continuations. Large bodies signal directional momentum; long wicks indicate rejection. Common patterns include the hammer (bullish reversal), doji (indecision), and shooting star (bearish reversal).",
  "identification_rules": [
    "A bullish candle has a close above its open; a bearish candle has a close below its open.",
    "A large bullish candle with minimal wicks signals strong bullish momentum.",
    "A large bearish candle with minimal wicks signals strong bearish momentum.",
    "A hammer is a candle with a small real body, a lower wick at least twice the body size, typically occurring in a downtrend or at a demand zone, signaling a potential bullish reversal.",
    "A doji has a very small real body (open and close nearly equal) and long wicks, indicating indecision.",
    "Weakening momentum is suggested by progressively smaller real bodies and longer wicks over consecutive candles.",
    "A candle with a longer lower wick indicates stronger bullish pressure than one with a shorter lower wick, assuming identical open, close, and high.",
    "Confirmation of a pattern occurs at the candle's close.",
    "At a supply zone, a bearish reversal pattern or strong bearish momentum candle signals potential downside.",
    "A shooting star is a candle with a small real body and a long upper wick, typically appearing in an uptrend, signaling a bearish reversal."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Candlestick patterns provide visual insight into market sentiment, signaling potential reversals or continuations. Traders use them to confirm entries at key levels (support/demand, resistance/supply), taking action upon the candle's close after the pattern forms. Patterns like the hammer near support indicate bullish rejection, while dojis reflect indecision preceding breakouts, and shooting stars suggest bearish reversals. Analyzing body and wick sizes assesses momentum strength, and patterns are most reliable when combined with structural confirmations such as breaks of structure or market structure shifts.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Assuming two candles with identical open, close, and high are equally bullish or bearish, ignoring that a longer lower wick indicates stronger buying pressure.",
    "Interpreting a candle's shape as a straight-line price movement, when in reality, price may have moved erratically between the open, high, low, and close.",
    "Entering a trade at a supply/demand zone without waiting for a confirming candlestick pattern.",
    "Forcing trades by anticipating a pattern before price reaches the zone or shows clear rejection.",
    "Misidentifying a hammer when the lower wick is not at least twice the body length."
  ],
